<CAPTION>  Photos (3); PHOTO: Julia Roberts, left, stars as a systematically abused wife
in 'Sleeping With the Enemy,' opening Feb. 8; six days later, Jodie Foster
opens in 'Silence of the Lambs.'; PHOTO: Demme, left, and PHOTO: Ruben are
both aiming for the mainstream  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  MOVIE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  PREPARE yourself for what could become the battle of the superstar thrillers.;
   About to go at it hammer-and-tongs -- or rather straight razor to straight
razor -- are 20th Century Fox's "Sleeping With the Enemy" and Orion Pictures'
"The Silence of the Lambs." Both are based on grim suspense novels. Both
concern resourceful heroines (Julia Roberts in "Sleeping," Oscar-winner Jodie
Foster in "Silence"). Both are the handiwork of respected, if offbeat,
Hollywood directors. And both have the makings of cold-sweat classics in the
"Psycho"/"Wait Until Dark" mold.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MOVIEGOERS WILL BE GIVEN A DOUBLE DOSE OF
SUSPENSE
TWO BIG-NAME THRILLERS GO TOE-TO-TOE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Film  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     More to the point, both are set to open the first half of February.
"Sleeping With the Enemy," based on the Nancy Price book and featuring the
very hot Roberts as a viciously pursued wife, is scheduled for Feb. 8;
"Silence," based on the best-seller by Thomas Harris, arrives six days later
-- on Valentine's Day. The unusual Thursday opening is meant as an advertising
ploy: Instead of the traditional pink bouquet, Orion will be sending us
something in a darker shade -- crimson red, to be exact.;    Predictably,
representatives at both studios are shrugging off the imminent box-office
battle. They say either they're not concerned or that when it comes to
well-tooled thrillers the public can't get its fill. If "Sleeping" is good,
the argument goes, it will make us eager for more clammy suspense and smooth
the way for "Silence.";    Sounds right, but you can still bet that the
respective studios are nervous. Already, they're sending out invitations to
media junkets. 20th Century Fox will unveil the $18-million "Sleeping" in Los
Angeles on Jan. 18; Orion has set its first critics' screenings for Jan. 24 in
Washington, D.C. Why D.C.? Because Foster's character is an intern for the
FBI. (Not above a little subliminal advertising, Fox Television slipped a
reference to a "Sleeping With the Enemy" screening into last Thursday's
episode of "L.A. Law.");    The films appear pretty evenly matched at this
point, though I'd give the edge to "Silence" because it's based on a big
best-seller and has a strong built-in following. From here, you have to weigh
the strengths of the individual talents involved. Foster may have the
best-actress Oscar (for "The Accused"), but she hasn't done much lately, and
"Pretty Woman" Roberts may be the most popular actress on the scene right
now.;    As for the filmmakers, they're both 40ish, have apprenticed on
low-budget action pictures, and are known for their ability to work quirky
spins on familiar material.;    Joseph Ruben was in the director's chair on
"Sleeping." He toiled for years as an exploitation filmmaker ("The Pom-Pom
Girls") before turning heads with "The Stepfather" and the excellent James
Woods vehicle, "True Believer." Jonathan Demme directed "Silence," a sequel to
Harris' "Red Dragon" (filmed in 1986 as "Manhunter"). His credits include
"Stop Making Sense," "Swimming to Cambodia," "Melvin and Howard," "Married to
the Mob" and, most important, "Something Wild." Of the two, Demme is more
seasoned. However, Ruben has, in the last few years, become one of our best
action directors. His prison-cafeteria rub-out at the beginning of "True
Believer" ranks as one of the best action sequences of the '80s.;    As for
the directors themselves, they're predictably high on their respective
movies.;    Demme is excited about going more mainstream, fashioning the kind
of nuts-and-bolts thriller in which Brian ("Dressed to Kill") DePalma once
excelled. "We nailed it!" he almost shouts. "It's a good one. We remained true
to the spirit of the book (about an FBI intern who uses an imprisoned serial
killer to track another killer) but came up with a lot of new twists. . . . It
took a tremendous amount of mental reprogramming for me to go from social
satire to an all-out thriller. That it represents something different is
delightful to me. I was ready for the challenge . . . to be freed from the
discipline of comedy.";    Ruben refers to "Sleeping," which co-stars Patrick
("Mountains of the Moon") Bergin as the deranged husband, as "a simple primal
idea about a woman who has been psychologically and physically kept down by a
very bad man. She tries to escape and he hunts her down.";    When told
"Sleeping" sounded like a number of recent TV movies about systematically
abused wives, Ruben replies, "We don't do naturalistic, kitchen-sink drama.
This is more of a stylized thriller. I'd say 'Hitchcockian,' but that's
pretentious.";    Ruben says he's not worried about the competition from
Orion. "I read half of 'Silence,' just to see what it was about. I'm not
concerned. They're both thrillers, but they're so different. Theirs sounds a
lot more violent. We don't have a lot of physical violence. That was the
challenge for me: To make a scary movie with a scary character who commits
very little physical violence. In 'Stepfather,' I had the villain beat someone
to death with a two-by-four. There's nothing like that here.";    Demme's
trump card? "A very different and realistic villain." Ruben's? His star,
naturally. "All I can say is, we're glad we have Julia Roberts."  </TEXT>
