<CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Jodie Foster: tough and terse; PHOTO: Scott Glenn turns
special agent Jack Crawford into a fascinating character.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  POLICE; MOVIE; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  HOLLYWOOD delivers a special Valentine's greeting today -- one that's drenched
in buckets of the sticky red stuff.;    It's called "The Silence of the
Lambs," and it co-stars Jodie Foster as an FBI trainee and Anthony Hopkins as
the imprisoned fiend who may just help her unravel a series of killings that
would make a coroner blanch.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  'LAMBS' TURNS SHEEPISH WHEN IT SHOULD GO
FOR THE THROAT  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Additional information attached to the end of this article.
Cover Story  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The source for "Silence," of course, is the 1988 Thomas Harrisbest seller.
Harris' "Red Dragon," filmed as "Manhunter," introduced us to the monstrous
genius of psychiatrist Hannibal Lecter, a.k.a. Hannibal the Cannibal.
"Silence," published seven years later, tells of the further misdeeds of Dr.
Lecter, who from his dungeon-like cell works -- or rather, pretends to work --
in tandem with FBI student Clarice Starling.;    Harris' thrillers are like
three-ring circuses. There's plenty to hold your attention, but it's sometimes
hard to figure out who's stalking whom.;    Michael Mann, in adapting "Red
Dragon," realized this; he streamlined the complicated narrative. Jonathan
Demme, best known for "Melvin and Howard" and "Something Wild," has taken a
different tack in filming "Silence." He has shoehorned all the characters and
plot twists of the book into two hours of screen time.;    The results are at
once laudable and maddening. Fans of the book, looking for an added jolt or
two as Demme and screenwriter Ted Tally stray from -- or, indeed, improve upon
-- Harris' sinister narrative, are in for a letdown. "Silence" the movie is
slavishly faithful, and this means anyone familiar with the book will always
be several giant steps ahead of heroine Starling.;    Those unfamiliar with
the novel will face other problems, the worst being a narrative that's far too
densely plotted.;    As in the book, FBI intern Starling is pressed into
service by the top man in Behavioral Science, special agent Jack Crawford
(Scott Glenn). Starling is sent to use her charm on Dr. Lecter, still the star
attraction at Baltimore's Hospital for the Criminally Insane. It's while
sparring with the wily Lecter that Starling learns of a connection between
Lecter and the currently at large "Buffalo Bill," who kidnaps young women and
then partially flays them.;    But there's little time for such cat-and-mouse
stuff. Bill has hit again, kidnapping the daughter of a Tennessee senator.
Suddenly the authorities are more than happy to placate Lecter, whom they
truss up like the Man in the Iron Mask and transport to Memphis to meet with
the girl's frantic mother (Diane Baker of "Marnie" in a rare screen
appearance).;    It's during this Memphis sojourn that Starling and her
superiors discover that Lecter, even under lock and key, is more dangerous
than the maniac he's supposedly helping track.;    Demme, who began his career
cranking out exploitation quickies like "Caged Heat," is no stranger to the
junk-thriller racket. Which is probably why we expected "Silence" to be more
of a sheer ride. As these things go, this one is almost polite in manner.
Obviously after a more mainstream audience, Demme leaves a lot to the
imagination. No quibble here. But apart from Lecter's ghastly Memphis
masquerade, the fright factor isn't nearly what it should be, considering the
source material. (The loudest audience reaction at a preview? A dry laugh --
in response to Starling's stammered "FBI -- you're safe now.");    Also, Demme
has favored the antagonistic student-teacher relationship between Starling and
Lecter at the expense of the Jame Gumb/Buffalo Bill character, a classic
mama's boy-gone-bad in the book. In the hands of actor Ted Levine, Gumb is
reduced to the kind of crazed transvestite Hollywood once blamed for all
unspeakable acts. Worse, Gumb/Bill is as much a cipher at the end as when we
first meet him.;    Foster, who won an Oscar as the rape victim in "The
Accused," gives a game and anything-but-glamorous performance. Her Starling is
a woman determined to succeed in a male-dominated profession, and Foster goes
considerably beyond Jamie Lee Curtis' rookie in "Blue Steel" to give us a
tough, terse portrayal of the eager-beaver student who jettisoned, long ago,
all extraneous feminine baggage.;    Though none of his character's dark
history remains, Scott Glenn turns FBI boss Crawford into a fascinating mix of
bureaucrat and proud father figure. Anthony Heald, as the taunting hospital
director anxious to cash in on his prize psycho, is even better. In fact,
Heald's jailer is the real villain of the piece. Hopkins capitulates that role
with a performance that's too showy to be terrifying. All glowering smiles and
bug-eyed retorts, he appears to be trying out for a silent version of "Dr.
Jekyll and Mr. Hyde.";    The best thing about "Silence" is the production
design by Kristi Zea ("GoodFellas"). Zea -- with a major assist from
cinematographer Tak Fujimoto -- has done a brilliant job of realizing Harris'
grimmer-than-grim charnel houses and dungeons. Take your choice -- Lecter's
subterranean lair, the Memphis court-house cage or Bill's basement pit. Each
is creepy beyond words.;    If only we could say as much for the entire
production. "Silence" cried out to be a nuts-and-bolts chiller, the kind of
grisly handiwork in which Tobe ("Texas Chainsaw Massacre") Hooper once
specialized. Demme and company might also have learned from Mann, who, for
"Manhunter," shrewdly went with a no-name cast and tawdry TV look. As a costly
star vehicle, "Silence" was muzzled from the start. It could only be so
outrageous, so shocking. Too bad. We were in the mood for a bona fide
throat-clutcher.;     The Silence of the Lambs; (star)(star) 1/2; Rated: R
(profanity, violence, grisly makeup effects); Cast: Jodie Foster, Anthony
Hopkins; Director: Jonathan Demme; Screenwriter: Ted Tally  </TEXT>
