<DESCRIPT>  MOVIE; RANKING  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE thrillers "The Silence of the Lambs" and "Sleeping With the Enemy" led the
holiday weekend box office pack, but "Dances With Wolves" rode its 12 Oscar
nods to new heights with a 41 percent rise in two-day revenues.;    Critically
acclaimed, "The Silence of the Lambs" made its debut with a $14.1 million
turnstile take on the holiday weekend, unseating "Sleeping With the Enemy,"
which placed second with $12.7 million, according to preliminary figures
supplied by Exhibitor Relations Co.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THRILLERS DOMINATE BOX OFFICE, BUT 'DANCES'
SOARS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Box Office  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The success of Orion Pictures' "The Silence of the Lambs," a nail-biter
featuring Jodie Foster as an FBI agent and Anthony Hopkins as a flesh-eating
killer, comes during hard times for the cash-poor studio.;    Orion met its
$12.5 million debt payment Friday, while other studios circled overhead for
rights to buy some Orion films at bargain-basement prices.;    In third place
was John Goodman's "King Ralph" and in fourth was "Home Alone.";    Orion's
"Dances With Wolves," which led the Academy Award contenders announced last
week with 12 nominations, including best picture, was in fifth place.;    It
had a 41 percent increase in business on Saturday and Sunday. It took in an
estimated $6.5 million in receipts for the three-day holiday weekend.  </TEXT>
