<LEADPARA>  MOVING more like a hare than a tortoise, "Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles II" was
the nation's most popular film for the second consecutive weekend, as Oscar
winners enjoyed a surge at ticket windows.;    The adventures of the
pizza-chomping, sewer-dwelling crime fighters collected $13 million for first
place in its second weekend. It has made $39.8 million to date, according to
figures released Monday by Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  OSCARS, TURTLES, WOLVES, LAMBS DOMINATE AMERICA'S
SILVER SCREENS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Director-star Kevin Costner's "Dances With Wolves" capitalized on its seven
Academy Award wins. The Western, which won the best-picture Oscar last week,
surged 44 percent to $5.4 million for third place, up from sixth place a week
ago.;    "The Silence of the Lambs," director Jonathan Demme's thriller, came
in second with $5.8 million.;    "Career Opportunities," a new comedy about a
man locked in a department store, premiered in fourth place on a gate of $4
million.;    Oliver Stone's "The Doors" slammed shut, falling off the leader
board after just a month of release.;    In addition to "Dances With Wolves,"
other Oscar winners took off at the box office.;    "Reversal of Fortune,"
whose star Jeremy Irons won the best actor trophy, advanced from $54,244 a
week ago to $521,556 this weekend on 242 more screens.;    Best supporting
actor winner Joe Pesci's "GoodFellas" moved from $216,991 to $344,351, and
supporting actress winner Whoopi Goldberg's "Ghost" accelerated from $200,329
to $230,550.;    In eighth was "Home Alone," the amazingly successful comedy
that is now set to pass "Jaws" as the fourth highest-grossing movie. "Home
Alone" made $2.4 million over the weekend and has drawn $256.8 million to
date. "Jaws" earned $260 million.;    "New Jack City," a drama about a New
York drug lord's downfall, made $3.7 million to place fifth.;    "Sleeping
With the Enemy," the Julia Roberts movie focusing on a battered wife, took
sixth on a gross of $3.2 million. The jurisprudence drama "Class Action"
slipped to seventh on revenues of $3 million.;    In ninth was "The Hard Way,"
a lighthearted drama looking at an actor playing a cop, on receipts of $2.1
million. The new musical movie "The Five Heartbeats" rounded out the Top 10
with proceeds of $1.6 million.;  Film Box Office Returns;    No. Title
