<CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Jodie Foster found an unexpected place for herself behind
the camera while making the movie 'Little Man Tate'; PHOTO: Foster plus a
death's head moth made 'The Silence of the Lambs' a hit  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  WOMAN; MOVIE; PROFESSIONAL; PROFILE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  WHEN Jodie Foster was a little girl, appearing in films such as "Napoleon and
Samantha" and on sitcoms such as "The Courtship of Eddie's Father," she would
tell people that she wanted to be "a talker" when she grew up.;   "When I was
a kid, I really enjoyed journalists and I was an incessant talker," she
recalls. "It was always like this big high for me to get to actually talk to
people about what I did."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Arts &amp; Books  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE FOSTER CHILD
THE GROWN-UP CHILD ACTRESS TURNS DIRECTOR  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Film; See also related article on page 16 of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Foster, now a poised and self-assured adult, still enjoys speaking publicly
about her work, and even admits to fantasizing on occasion about becoming a TV
talk-show host. She seemed well-suited to that calling as she deftly fielded
questions from reporters at the 16th annual Festival of Festivals recently.;  
The 28-year-old actress was in Toronto to attend the film festival, where her
latest movie made its Canadian debut. With "Little Man Tate" (which opened
locally Friday), Foster has achieved another childhood ambition: to direct a
movie. It's something she has wanted to do since she was about 10 and first
"knew that the power on the movie was the director.";   The boy genius; A
contemporary comedy-drama about growing up, "Little Man Tate" is the story of
a 7-year-old prodigy named Fred Tate (played by newcomer Adam Hann-Byrd), his
down-to-earth mother (Foster) and a brilliant psychologist (Dianne Wiest).
Foster, who was something of a precocious child herself, admitted that the
film contains "autobiographical references" but quickly added that it is "not
autobiographical" in the strict sense.;   For Foster, one of the perks of
making "Little Man Tate" was working with Adam and the other children in the
film, which she loved because of the "purity" of their motives as actors.;  
"You can't bribe them with more money or something," she said. "If they don't
want to throw the spaghetti, they just don't throw it. There's something
absolutely beautiful about that.";   In her unmistakable, subtly husky voice,
Foster explained that she picked Adam (a bright New Yorker, but not an
official genius) because of the steely concentration he displayed in an
audition.;   "There were, like, ambulances, and people making noises in
another room, and somebody dropped something, and somebody walked in, and not
once did he ever waver at all," she said. "He just continued to read his page.
There's something about that kind of concentration span which is, I think,
ultimately what acting is about.";   Foster said the primary draw of the
script (by Scott Frank, who wrote the first draft while a college student),
however, was its broader message about the struggle of growing up different
from others.;   "It takes time to be an unconventional person in a
terrifically conventional world," she reflected, looking deceptively
conformist in her gray slacks and chic purple blazer. "It takes a lot of work
to figure out how to put yourself apart and say, 'I will be different, but I
will be healthy.' ";   Although Foster fiercely guards her private life now,
her uniquely different and presumably healthy early years are an open book
that most moviegoers have read at least part of.;   Youngest of four children,
the Los Angeles-born Foster was raised by her divorced mother, Evelyn "Brandy"
Foster, and has seen her father only a few times. In the early days, Brandy
often jokingly referred to her daughter as an "immaculate conception" -- words
Fred's mother uses about him in "Little Man Tate.";   The baby star;   At age
3, Foster got her start in show business by appearing in television
commercials as the pigtailed Coppertone Girl. Commercials led to sitcoms,
which in turn led to roles in such films as "Bugsy Malone," "Alice Doesn't
Live Here Anymore" and "The Little Girl Who Lives Down the Lane.";   Hollywood
began to take her seriously after her unforgettable performance as a
12-year-old hooker in "Taxi Driver," for which she snagged an Oscar
nomination.;   As she headed for college in 1980, Foster seemed, for the first
time, to be on the threshold of leading a relatively "normal" life. But after
John Hinckley shot President Reagan in a twisted attempt to impress her,
normalcy was no longer possible.;   "It's funny to be someone everyone has an
opinion about," Foster once told the New York Times. And for a while, her
dubious renown as Hinckley's "inspiration" overshadowed her hard-won fame as
an actress.;   "The Accused" changed that. After graduating from Yale -- where
she studied African-American culture and appeared in a play for the first and
only time ("a mixed experience") -- she won an Oscar for portraying a rape
victim in the 1988 movie. She followed up that triumph with this year's "The
Silence of the Lambs," a certifiable hit in which she starred as intrepid FBI
trainee Clarice Starling.;   The way "Silence" director Jonathan Demme tells
it, Foster practically directed herself in that picture. "At first, it sort of
surprised me how much I liked what she came up with," Demme told a reporter
for Premiere magazine during filming.;   It was, you might say, only a matter
of time before Foster would realize her directorial ambitions.;   "I've always
tried to do exactly what I've wanted to do in terms of my career," she said.
"What's great about film making is that if you are an arrogant person like
myself -- or an ego-driven person like myself, and I don't say that in a
pejorative way -- you just forge ahead. So much of it is about confidence.";  
Foster does sound sure of herself as she speaks about her plans to take on
future acting, directing and producing projects.;   She has already filmed --
and soon will be seen briefly in -- Woody Allen's upcoming "Shadows and Fog."
She also sounds charged up about a sequel to "The Silence of the Lambs," when
and if it is made. As for "Little Man Tate," it went into general release on
Oct. 9.;   Perhaps the most unusual thing about the unusual production is that
the director -- rather than an executive of the studio, Orion Pictures -- was
the one to insist it end on an upbeat note.;   "I'll tell you one thing, I'm
probably the only director in the world that actually had to fight for a happy
ending," she said wryly. "Nobody else was as convinced that Fred could have a
happy life as I (was). . . . I didn't want the movie to end, 'Well, if you're
smart you'll have a rotten life, but at least you'll have your mom.' ";  
Foster sees more than one path to happiness -- which she thinks of as an
elusive state, in any case.;   "I don't think happiness is something you just
kind of deserve," she says authoritatively. "I think you have to work for it."
