<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
   Film: Weirdo Killer Shrink Meets the G-Girl
   ----
   By Julie Salamon
</HL>
<DATE>
02/14/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<LP>
   Dr. Hannibal Lector, the villain-hero of "The Silence of
the Lambs," is most monstrous -- most terrifying -- when he's
most civil. He is kept in a glass cage because he has dined
on human tongues and livers. Clearly this is a gruesome guy.
But he is most shocking when his behavior doesn't conform to
whatever suits your worst fantasy of depravity. He is most
horrifying when he's polite.
   Hannibal Lector, this bloody killer, can be dismissed when
he's a monster. He's not so easy to dismiss when he's someone
not very different from you. Coming from his mouth, a casual
compliment -- "Love your suit" -- becomes something vile.
You'd want to burn the suit just because he liked it, because
he used your clothes, your taste to link you with him, a
psychopath. But even after you'd burned the suit you wouldn't
forget. From then on, anyone who told you your hair was nice,
your scarf was lovely, that person would be suspect.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Jonathan Demme's film version of the Thomas Harris novel
leaves you with that thought -- anyone has killer potential
-- and that is its brilliance. If Lector personifies one's
worst fear, then Mr. Demme has found the ultimate Lector in
the person of Anthony Hopkins. Sly and urbane, Mr. Hopkins is
utterly credible as this psychiatrist genius and informed
snob, who is also a cannibalistic murderer. Lector knows the
difference between good wine and swill, and can spot cheap
shoes in an instant. Mr. Hopkins has a way of making his own
intelligence seem nasty as he creates this nightmare: The
shrink who sees into your soul and uses what he finds to lure
you.
   Lector isn't an ordinary murderer and he isn't used in an
ordinary way in this mesmerizing story about an FBI agent's
hunt for a serial killer. Lector becomes an FBI adviser in
more ways than one. The FBI, which is trying to track down
another serial killer, sends a young agent -- a smart,
attractive woman -- to Lector's cell to see if she can elicit
some clues from him. Lector immediately tries to turn the
meeting into a different kind of session. He tries to
psychoanalyze her.
   The movie is propelled by the G-girl's efforts to stop the
killer before he kills again -- he's kidnapped his next
victim. Working with his usual collaborators, including
cinematographer Tak Fujimoto and editor Craig McKay, Mr.
Demme uses the story as an excuse for yet another of his
odysseys into bizarre corners of America. Though "Silence of
the Lambs" is a crisp, taut thriller, it also is the story of
people looking for something in very strange places.
   Jodie Foster plays Clarice Starling, the sturdy FBI
trainee with the name of a romance-novel heroine. She's
chosen for the assignment because she's smart and tough --
and because she's pretty and might appeal to Lector, who has
been holed up in the sub-basement of a hospital for the
criminally insane for eight years.
   Mr. Demme uses Ms. Foster's femaleness in an interesting
way. The film opens, to suitably scary music, with her
jogging through the woods. She could be a victim. Then you
see her climbing and swinging across an obstacle course. She
seems to be in some sort of training. Soon it's made clear
that she's training to become an FBI agent. Just when you
might start thinking of her as some kind of superwoman, she
steps into an elevator and some large men follow. She's a
small figure in gray; they're behemoths in red.
   All of this happens very quickly but to make a point.
Starling is an attractive woman of unexceptional size doing
what used to be thought of as a man's job and that's an
inescapable fact. Sometimes it's explicit -- as when the
nerdiest researcher immediately asks her for a date -- and
sometimes it isn't. But there's an extra layer of implied
sexuality in every move she makes -- even taking her
assignment from her blandly spooky boss, played by Scott
Glenn.
   Ms. Foster makes Starling seem wonderfully clear. She's
aware of the affect she has on men and uses it to her
advantage without flirting, or deviating from her purpose.
There are implications that she's motivated by the early
death of her policeman father. But she's allowed to be
steady. If her bravery and single-mindedness are
manifestations of neurosis, she's permitted not to appear
neurotic. She is a rare heroine, a woman who goes about her
work the way men do in movies, without seeming less a woman.
   Mr. Demme never cheapens Starling by making her cute or
weird. He understands that as our guide into this sinister
world, she has to be steady. That doesn't mean that Mr. Demme
has abandoned his affection for eccentrics and oddballs. The
director learned his trade from B-movie master Roger Corman
-- who plays a bit part in "Lambs." Mr. Demme skillfully uses
what he learned from Mr. Corman about horror grotesques
without injecting a campy feel into this film. Starling meets
Lector in the lower depths of a creepy brick asylum. But
there's a twist in this descent into hell. She walks through
a dark corridor, trying not to stare at the psycho-killers
huddled in their conventional cells. Lector, however, seems
like a space-age killer. His cell is brightly lit and
separated from the rest by thick glass. He's like a lab
specimen.
   Mr. Demme has populated this journey into the heart's
darkness with the kind of eccentrics who have attracted him
before, in "Something Wild," in "Melvin and Howard," in
"Married to the Mob." Anthony Heald is particularly creepy as
the asylum chief who's locked in a weird struggle with
Lector; one senses the prison psychiatrist hates his
celebrated patient not so much because he's a murderer but
because he's so much smarter. Brooke Smith is refreshingly
spunky as the chubby young woman the serial killer on the
loose has picked to hit next. And the entomologists are
perfect.
   ---
   VIDEO TIP: Mr. Demme's films are so inventive that one of
his earlier films, "Last Embrace," is interesting primarily
because it's so perfectly derivative of Hitchcock. In that
film, which starred Roy Scheider as a hunted man, Mr. Demme
solemnly "paid homage to" "Vertigo," "The Birds," "North by
Northwest," "Psycho," and possibly others.
</TEXT>
