<HEAD>Entertainment Briefs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orion Pictures has scheduled the release of
Jonathan Demme's new thriller, ``The Silence of the Lambs,'' for
Feb. 14, 1991.
   Though debuting on Valentine's Day, the film is by no means a
romance. Based on the shocking best-selling novel by Thomas Harris,
``The Silence of the Lambs'' stars Academy Award-winner Jodie
Foster as Clarice Starling, a gutsy FBI trainee haunted by her
past, who risks her life in an attempt to save a missing woman from
death.
   ``The Silence of the Lambs'' co-stars Anthony Hopkins, Scott
Glenn, Jack Crawford and Dianne Baker.
   ---&equals;
  ENGLAND (AP) - Mary Elizabeth Mastrantonio will portray Maid
Marian, and Alan Rickman will play the Sheriff of Nottingham in
Morgan Creek's ``Robin Hood: Prince of Thieves,'' which stars Kevin
Costner in the title role.
   The Warner Bros. release, currently shooting for 13 weeks in
England and France, is set for release next year.
   The production is currently shooting deep in the ancient forests
of Central England, where Robin Hood's legendary Sherwood Forest
has been re-created.
   In December, the production will travel to the ancient walled
city of Carcassone, France, to authentically depict the medieval
city of Nottingham.
   This adaptation of the classic tale of the swashbuckling hero of
Nottingham Forest also stars Morgan Freeman and Christian Slater.
   ---&equals;
   NEW YORK (AP) - Cameron Mackintosh's hit London musical ``Miss
Saigon,'' will open on Broadway in March 1991 at the Broadway
Theater, where another Mackintosh hit, ``Les Miserables,'' is
currently in its fourth year.
   ``Les Miserables'' will move to another Shubert theater late in
1990 to make way for the arrival of ``Miss Saigon.''
   ``Miss Saigon'' tells a tragic story of love and self-sacrifice
involving a young Vietnamese girl and an American soldier at the
time of the fall of Saigon in 1975.
   ``Miss Saigon'' had its world premiere in September 1989 at the
Theater Royal, Drury Lane, opening with the largest advance sale in
the history of the West End.
</TEXT>
