<CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: No illness, reports Tandy camp; PHOTO: Wilder's 'Sherlock'
coming back.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  CELEBRITY; QA  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  REPORTS that Jessica Tandy is undergoing chemotherapy treatment for cancer are
drawing denials from the 81-year-old actress' reps (who say "she's perfectly
fine") -- and from NBC and producers Jordan Kerner and Jon Avnet. Tandy is set
to start production of the network's "The Story Lady" next month. In June, the
esteemed performer is scheduled to begin work on the Avnet-Kerner film of
"Fried Green Tomatoes at the Whistle Stop Cafe." "We've done readings with her
already and she's glorious," Kerner says. "That (her illness) happened a long
time ago. She's fine now."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  TANDY CANCER RUMORS ELICIT DENIALS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Grapevine  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  From Liz Smith in New York; COMEBACK CLUE: Director Billy Wilder made his last
movie, "Buddy, Buddy," in 1981. But he reveals that one of his favorites, "The
Private Life of Sherlock Holmes," will be revived in the current "Spartacus"
and "Lawrence of Arabia" fashion.;    In 1970, Wilder directed Robert
Stephens, Colin Blakely, Genevieve Page, Christopher Lee and Stanley Holloway
in this movie made in England. Though little seen, it became a classic. Some
critics called it "Great!" saying it was "the least embittered and by far
Wilder's most moving film.";    "Sherlock Holmes," made for
UA/Phalanx-Mirisch, was meant to run three delicious hours. Naturally, it was
cut to something more "manageable" for its 1970 release. Now Wilder, a
multi-Oscar winner, promises it will be restored, re-edited and rereleased in
all its original glory.;    BOX-OFFICE NOISE: Orion execs, who have had their
headaches of late, are ecstatic over the grosses that have made "The Silence
of the Lambs" the first 1991 release to hit the $100 million mark. Now they
are jumping up and down over Jodie Foster's new one, "Little Man Tate," in
which she stars and directs -- it has already been touted as an Academy Award
contender.;    That could prove to be an embarrassment of riches for Orion and
Foster come next March. Oscar in 1992 will definitely consider both Foster and
her "Lambs" co-star, Anthony Hopkins, as nominees. His portrayal of Hannibal
Lecter is bound to be in the running.;    AUDREY'S AURA: Lincoln Center and
its denizens seemed absolutely transformed by the mere presence of Audrey
Hepburn as the Film Society honored her the other night in New York. No one --
not even Elizabeth Taylor or Bette Davis -- managed to pack them in the way
Hepburn did.;    It was SRO from the word go. Wilder, Stanley Donen, Harry
Belafonte, Tony Perkins, Alan Arkin, Gregory Peck and Ralph Lauren saluted
Hepburn from the stage. Arkin said to the audience: "Even my own family has
never forgiven me for tormenting Audrey in 'Wait Until Dark.' "; HERE TODAY:
The "Today" show wanted its West Coast medical expert, Dr. Art Ulene, to move
to New York. He didn't want to, and the show is now seeking a woman to replace
him.; From Marilyn Beck and Stacy Jenel Smith in Hollywood;    UNSETTLING
ISSUE: After nearly seven years, there is still no end in sight to the legal
war between James Mason's widow, Clarissa Kaye, and Mason offspring Morgan and
Portland. Not only does the estate remain unsettled, but the children of the
actor (who died in July 1984 in Switzerland) have reportedly yet to convince
their stepmother to disclose the whereabouts and disposition of their father's
remains.;    "It's a nightmare," says the 35-year-old Morgan, a Hollywood film
producer ("sex, lies and videotapes").  </TEXT>
