<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Jodie Foster befriends jailed psychopath Anthony Perkins,
center, in her search for a serial killer in 'The Silence of Lambs,' also
starring Scott Glenn, rear.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  MOVIE; PSYCHOLOGY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE perversely twisted mind has always been a favorite subject of
storytellers. From Iago to Norman Bates, Vladimir Nabokov's Humbert Humbert to
David Lynch's Leland Palmer/Bob, the logic of villainy has been fictionally
explored, on the page, the stage and the screen, over and over.;    Even when
failed by their powers of sheer imagining, writers and actors have drawn
inspiration from grim reality: Jack the Ripper, Lizzie Borden, Gary Gilmore,
Charles Manson -- not to mention Adolf Hitler, Joseph Stalin and Richard III.
By now, Saddam Hussein is undoubtedly a twinkle in some wordsmith's eye.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Arts &amp; Books  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BAD DEEDS SHINE ON SCREEN
POWER OF THE PERVERSE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Film  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Clearly, evil is alluring, and not just to those who would dramatize it.
From mild naughtiness to vicious criminality, the performance of bad deeds is
something the rest of the population evidently wants to know about.;    This
is one way to explain why the psychopath, that personification of remorseless
evildoing, has such an established place in the public consciousness.;    The
most current example of the psychopath in popular narrative art is the one
portrayed by Anthony Hopkins in the new film "The Silence of the Lambs," a
character Hopkins describes, with thoroughly pleasant detachment, as
"horrifyingly insane.";    At dinner recently in a Manhattan bistro, Hopkins,
53, is a regular Joe, more or less, albeit with a British accent, eager enough
to converse but not entirely comfortable dining with a stranger. It might be a
little less comfortable for a stranger who has just seen "The Silence of the
Lambs," because in it, Hopkins' character, Dr. Hannibal Lecter, is a man who
makes his favorite meals of human flesh and blood.;    The film, which opened
on Valentine's Day, is an adaptation of the page-turning chiller by Thomas
Harris about the psychopathic Lecter -- "Hannibal the Cannibal," as he's known
in the tabloid press -- a brilliant psychiatrist who has long been imprisoned
for a series of grisly murders and whose insight is solicited by the FBI to
help in apprehending a depraved serial killer still on the loose.;    Directed
by Jonathan Demme, the film stars Jodie Foster as Clarice Starling, the young
FBI agent sent to question Lecter in his maximum security cell and who, in the
course of tracking down the new killer, ends up forming an unsettling,
mind-bending bond with the old one.;    Though Lecter is a supporting role and
the story unfolds from Starling's point of view, his personality is the source
of the film's terror. Intellectually powerful, culturally refined, innately
curious and possessed of exquisite manners, Lecter is an evil genius, the
embodiment of mysterious, inexplicable and unmitigated perversity.;    "We
managed to save one of her eyes," Starling is told about a nurse who got too
close to an untrussed Lecter during a medical exam and had her face literally
eaten.;    Seeing death's messenger;    It is not the sort of role, in other
words, for which an actor can plumb his own life experience. Indeed, Hopkins,
who is not a Method actor, says that as he was reading the script, "the part
came off the page into my brain. I knew the voice. I knew what he looked like.
I don't know why, but the impression was left in me of a kind of dark angel of
death. The most peculiar thing was the name.;    "Lecter. Hannibal Lecter. The
Lecter sound. It started like a kind of clock in my brain. Lecter. And I saw a
black box, like a black clock, something black and shiny, something veneered,
a lacquered black killing machine. He was mechanical. All the onomatopoeic
associations of the name. I put the image together, and when I came over from
London to do it, I'd already decided on the physical nature of it.";    Still,
preparing is not performing, and the Lecter role is precisely the sort that
makes a viewer wonder about the experience of inhabiting such a character. It
seems reasonable to expect that one wouldn't want to live inside such a man
for long, that it might give an actor the creeps -- or worse.;    Dancing with
devils;    Hopkins' visceral response to the suggestion is just the opposite:;
   "It was great fun," he says. "What it is for an actor is a great chance to
play a game, to flirt with something that's so diabolical, knowing it's only a
fiction. During that scene where I was tearing the guy's face off" -- he does
this with his teeth -- "we had a rubber bone, and I had one end and he had the
other. And Jonathan would say, 'Cut,' and I'd say, 'This is a hell of a way to
make a living, isn't it?' ";    If one considers the roll call of murderous
madmen presented in the culture lately -- a slew of recent theatrical films,
for instance, most notably "Misery," the Rob Reiner adaptation of Stephen
King's novel, and the television movies that filled up sweeps week -- it seems
clear that people are more curious than ever about that which most truly
repels them. It's as if the culture is asking collectively, "Just what will
those wackos be up to next?";    "It's unfortunate that, in our society,
killers can become celebrities," wrote Ronald Markman, a forensic psychiatrist
in Los Angeles, in his 1989 book "Alone With the Devil," which recounts his
experiences interviewing murderers. "Our morbid fascination with them is
simple human nature.";    Markman contends that the appeal of the psychopath
is actually a form of identification. "There is something inside them that is
also inside us," he wrote, "and we are attracted to them so we can find out
what that something is.";    The accepted clinical definition of a psychopath,
or sociopath (the terms are interchangeable), has to do with an absence of
superego, that part of the mind that governs self-criticism and enforces moral
standards.;    A psychopath, in other words, is someone without a conscience.
In a recent telephone interview, Markman explained further:;    "The
psychopathic individual is psychologically an infant in an adult body. An
infant does what he wants to do when he wants to do it. The internal policeman
develops ordinarily between 2 and 7. In some people it never develops. In
some, it is deficient.;    "The psychopath, basically, is an individual who
functions at the level of providing pleasure for himself at the expense of
others around him. He doesn't care about the consequence of treating people as
objects.";    And why would other people identify with someone like this? "We
were born that way, without any superego." And what about acting? Is it
possible to pretend convincingly? "Anyone can play the part," Markman said.
"We're all psychopaths under the skin." (box)  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  BRUCE WEBER, New York Times  </BYLINE>
