<LEADPARA>  A SERIES of new films starring prestigious artists has been placed in virtual
cold storage because Orion Pictures, which made them, faces severe financial
difficulties.;   Film executives close to Orion, a small studio with a record
of critically acclaimed movies, said that the decision to keep the movies on
the shelf was especially painful because several of them, and their stars, are
believed to have Academy Award potential. The films must be released in the
next two months to be considered for Oscar nominations.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ORION'S MONEY TROUBLES MAY TAKE BIG NAMES OUT OF
OSCAR RACE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Movies  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Luminous names;   Among the stars are Michelle Pfeiffer, Beau Bridges,
Cybill Shepherd, Woody Allen, Jodie Foster and Madonna. Orion executives say
that several of the films are especially strong, including "Love Field," with
Pfeiffer and Dennis Haysbert, about a white woman and black man who meet
unexpectedly in Dallas on the day JFK is assassinated. The drama's director,
Jonathan Kaplan, also directed "The Accused," which won an Academy Award for
Foster.;   Another film, "Article 99," about the bureaucratic chaos at a
Veterans Administration hospital, has also stirred heavy interest at the
studio and among film makers who have seen it. Its stars include Ray Liotta,
Kiefer Sutherland, John Mahoney and Kathy Baker.;   Woody Allen, who made
"Annie Hall" and most of his other films at Orion, has completed what is
described by one Orion executive as a "philosophical comedy" set in the 1920s.
"Shadows and Fog" has a typically Allenesque cast, including Kathy Bates, Mia
Farrow, Foster, Madonna and Lily Tomlin.;   Because of Orion's inability to
finance Allen's next movie, he signed a deal with Tristar Pictures. At Orion,
Allen had almost total control over the production and editing of his films,
an unusual measure of creative freedom in Hollywood but not especially unusual
at Orion, which has been extraordinarily popular among film makers because --
unlike the major studios -- it has given them substantial independence.;  
Midge Sanford, producer of "Love Field" with partner Sarah Pillsbury, said:
"They're a wonderful company to work with. When they decide to do a movie,
they basically say, yes, let the film maker do it. They watch the budget but
aren't intrusive, and . . . that's welcome.";   The Sanford-Pillsbury team,
which now works out of the 20th Century Fox studios, made two other films at
Orion, "Desperately Seeking Susan" and "Eight Men Out." Sanford said other
studios would not have made those movies. "We have material that's often
offbeat or not obviously commercial," she said. "Orion takes risks.;   "It is
frustrating when a movie like 'Love Field' is ready to be released and it's
not released for reasons out of your control." Several months ago, Sanford
said, she was told the film might be released in February 1992.;   A
'welcoming place';   "It is Oscar caliber," she added. "A wonderful script. If
Orion is able to get its finances together, we would definitely work with them
again. It's a very welcoming place.";   Two of the most critically acclaimed
and financially successful movies in the last year were made for Orion.
"Dances With Wolves," the Kevin Costner movie about American Indians, cost
less than $20 million and has grossed more than $130 million domestically.
"The Silence of the Lambs," the Jonathan Demme terror film, also cost less
than $20 million, and has grossed more than $130 million; it is also expected
to win a number of Academy Awards.;   But the company, founded in 1982 by New
York lawyer Arthur B. Krim as an offshoot of United Artists, has also had its
major duds, including "She Devil," "State of Grace" and "The Hot Spots.";  
Film executives say that the company was highly vulnerable at the outset
because it had no major outside sources of income, as other studios did. "This
business has its ups and down," said one former Orion executive. "Orion did
not have deep enough pockets to survive the bad times.";   Because of
financial pressures, Orion sold off potentially lucrative foreign theatrical
rights and failed to expand into money-making fields like videos, records or
television. Two weeks ago Daily Variety published an internal Orion plan that
called for sharp reductions in overhead, the consolidation of Orion offices in
Los Angeles and an overhaul of film production and marketing and distribution
strategies.;   Orion is currently negotiating with banks to extend payment
terms on three past-due loans totaling $52 million. John Kluge, the
billionaire whose other interests include the Metromedia Co., owns about 70
percent of Orion.;   About a half-dozen completed films remain unreleased,
largely because of high publicity costs. Studio executives say it costs at
least $10 million, often more, for advertising and prints.  </TEXT>
