<DESCRIPT>  MOVIE; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  SOME random observations, digs and predictions for the new year:;   (check)
Movies used to be the most inexpensive of diversions. Now, at almost $7 a peek
($8 in New York and Los Angeles), they've become a major family expenditure.
Little wonder Americans, strapped at Christmastime, opted for something more
tangible, such as paying the electric bill.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  A QUICK REWIND
AND A FEW FAST CUTS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     (check) The holiday movies took us down the Amazon ("At Play in the Fields
of the Lord"), to a back-lot Neverland ("Hook"), to post-war Hollywoodland
("Bugsy") and to Dallas on that fateful fall day in '63 ("JFK"). The terrain
most of them failed to explore: the human heart. "The Prince of Tides" was the
notable exception.;   (check) Think of it as a marriage forged in hell:
Legendary paranoiac Jim Garrison has found a champion in film maker Oliver
Stone, whose "JFK" must rank as the most skillful and eloquent piece of
propaganda since Leni Riefenstahl's Nazi masterpiece, "Triumph of the Will."; 
 (check) Someone should tap Kenneth Branagh to play William Kennedy Smith.
He's just thin-lipped and blank-faced enough to be effective. The accent
should be a snap. (We'll check in later for your pick for Waldo, inconspicuous
hero of the inevitable "Where's Waldo? -- The Movie.");   (check) There was a
noticeable dearth in foreign product this year as exhibitors made room for
such dime-store gems as "Highlander 2" and "Late for Dinner." Has the movie
industry pulled off the kind of "Buy American" boycott Detroit still dreams of
mounting?;   (check) Hollywood keeps churning out high-tech thrillers, but it
longs to lose its heart. Half of the directors interviewed this year,
including Paul Schrader and John Frankenheimer, said they want to turn to
adult romance.;   (check) What kind of movie year will '92 be? In a word:
Noisy. In the wings are serial rapists ("Love Crimes"), psychotic men-haters
("Basic Instinct"), Mutt-and-Jeff cop comedies ("Lethal Weapon 3") and
future-world bounty hunters (Mick Jagger in "Freejack").;   (check) If anybody
out there knows what Bill ("Local Hero") Forsyth and Stanley ("Full Metal
Jacket") Kubrick are up to, please call. Hollywood needs an emergency
transfusion of their trends-be-damned approach.;   (check) Warren Beatty as
Bugsy and Bette Midler as a USO trouper in "For the Boys" appear to have a
lock on the best actor and actress Oscars. How about the supporting
categories? No contest. They should go to Rip Torn for his amiably preoccupied
lawyer in "Defending Your Life" and Diane Ladd for her plain-speaking mother
in "Rambling Rose.";   (check) And, in the "Which Movie Did He See?" category,
top honors to "Last Boy Scout" director Tony Scott for describing Bruce
Willis' foulmouthed P.I. as "sensitive" and "complex.";   (check) File this
under Nesting with a Vengeance. Newlyweds Brian DePalma and producer Gale Anne
Hurd, juggling caring for their first-born with their first film collaboration
("Raising Cain"), told Bay Area location scouts: "All locations must be within
a 20-minute drive of our new home in Woodside.";   (check) If there's still
doubt that nudity and hot-house sex are passe, check out "Bugsy," "Grand
Canyon" (arriving Jan. 10) and "The Prince of Tides." All three leave that
first night of pure bliss to the imagination. The new trend may be toward male
nudity: see Tom Berenger in "At Play in the Fields of the Lord," Kevin Costner
in "Robin Hood" and "Dances with Wolves" and De Niro in "Cape Fear.";  
(check) Most overrated film of '91: "Silence of the Lambs." Most underrated:
Paul Schrader's "The Comfort of Strangers" and Abel Ferrara's "King of New
York.";   (check) Schlockmeister Roger Corman must be having a good howl. He
oversaw the apprenticeships of Jonathan Demme, Martin Scorsese, Jonathan
Kaplan and Francis Coppola and now, all these years later, Corman's star
pupils have graduated to prestige slasher films, such as "Silence of the
Lambs," "Cape Fear," "Sleeping With the Enemy" and, upcoming from Coppola,
"Bram Stoker's Dracula."  </TEXT>
