<HL>
   Movies:
   Oscar Nominees
   Can Count On
   Box Office Gains
   ----
   By Laura Landro
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
02/13/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   TWX OPC SNE PCI PCC CRC MC NWS
</CO>
<IN>
RECREATION, ENTERTAINMENT, TOYS, MOVIES, PHOTOGRAPHY, SPORTS (REC)
</IN>
<LP>
   After grossing about $41 million following its release
last September, the Warner Brothers mob movie "Goodfellas" is
eking out business in just 22 theaters, down from a peak of
more than 1,300 screens.
   This morning, though, comes the Big Announcement: Academy
Award nominations. With some other awards and critics' 10
best lists for "Goodfellas" under its belt, Warner felt
confident enough by last Monday to book the movie into about
550 more theaters, starting Friday.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "This is our shot," says Rob Friedman, head of advertising
and publicity for the Time Warner Inc. unit. "We feel there's
an opportunity with all the recognition we've received, and
we hope the Academy has recognized us too."
   As the leftover 1990 movies slug it out with 1991
releases, studios are counting on critical kudos to give last
year's films one last shot at the box office. History shows
that Oscar nominations do help increase ticket sales. And
actually winning one of the coveted awards from the Academy
of Motion Picture Arts &amp; Sciences on March 25 is worth even
more. The Oscar for best picture can increase a film's total
box office revenue by $30 million to $40 million, according
to Philip Garfinkle, president of the box office data concern
Entertainment Data Inc.
   This year, though, the 1990 films that may get a nod from
the Oscar nominations face tough competition in the
marketplace. Some, like "Goodfellas," have been out of the
public eye for a while. Others, like "Godfather Part III,"
are still in hundreds of theaters but never made a big splash
to begin with, and are slowly losing steam to such hot
newcomers as Twentieth Century Fox Film Inc.'s "Sleeping with
the Enemy." Last weekend, the romantic thriller starring
Julia Roberts opened to an impressive $13.8 million, managing
to knock Fox's own blockbuster, "Home Alone," out of first
place.
   At the same time, for a movie that is already a big hit,
award nominations may not increase business much further. One
movie considered a shoo-in for Oscar nominations -- Orion
Pictures Corp.'s "Dances with Wolves" -- has taken in more
than $103 million since Nov. 9. After initially releasing the
movie on 13 screens, Orion raised the number of screens to
1,300, then added another 200 screens recently in
anticipation of the Academy Award nominations.
   David Forbes, president of distribution for Orion, notes
that the movie has played "very consistently" since its
release, registering its only major drop last weekend, when
ticket sales fell off about 18%. "Obviously there's a
substantial amount of business already in the picture," says
Mr. Forbes. "My anticipation is that the nominations will
give us a good boost, though not an enormous one, and it will
last 10 days to two weeks."
   "Dances with Wolves" made an impressive sweep of the
Golden Globe awards. Though not as prestigious as the Academy
Awards, Golden Globes are often an indicator of how the Oscar
nominations will go. The movie was named best dramatic motion
picture, its star and director Kevin Costner got best
director, and its screenplay by Michael Blake won as well.
Orion has done some advance campaigning for the Oscars,
sending script excerpts and copies of a book of photographs
from the movie to Academy members.
   "Dances with Wolves" is a rarity; it has won both critical
acclaim and big box office success. The Academy often ignores
commercial blockbusters, nominating small arty films such as
last year's "Henry V" and "My Left Foot," or epic movies such
as "Gandhi," "Chariots of Fire" and "The LastEmperor." If
past trends are any indication, the big movies of 1990 --
"Home Alone," "Ghost," "Pretty Woman" and "Teenage Mutant
Ninja Turtles" -- aren't likely to garner any of the
important Oscar nomination categories.
   Hollywood pundits say the 1990 crop of best picture
candidates include "Awakenings," which stars Robert DeNiro
and Robin Williams and was released by Sony Corp.'s Columbia
Pictures unit; Warner's "Goodfellas," "Hamlet" and "Reversal
of Fortune"; Paramount Pictures Corp.'s "Godfather Part III";
and MGM-Pathe Communications Co.'s "Russia House." Some
longshots include "Avalon," a movie released by Sony's
Tri-Star unit, Columbia's "Postcards From the Edge" and two
more recent films that independent producer Miramax Films has
in limited release, "The Grifters" and "Mr. &amp; Mrs. Bridge."
   But some executives say this year is a tough call. "The
high quality movies and sure-fire winners aren't there like
they were in the past," says John Krier, president of
Exhibitor Relations Co., which analyzes box office data.
   Even with Oscar nominations to lure audiences, the films
will face tough competition over the next few weeks from an
unusally high number of new releases such as "Sleeping with
the Enemy." Tri-Star just released "L.A. Story," a Steve
Martin comedy produced by Carolco Pictures Inc. that grabbed
the No. 2 spot at the box office last weekend with $6.7
billion in ticket sales.
   Tomorrow, Orion opens psychological thriller "The Silence
of the Lambs," which stars Jodie Foster, and Matsushita
Electric Industrial Co.'s Universal Studios unit opens a John
Goodman comedy, "King Ralph." On Feb. 22, Paramount is
opening a romantic comedy, "He Said, She Said," and on March
1, Tri-Star opens another Carolco movie, "The Doors," about
the late rock star Jim Morrison.
   Mark Manson, an analyst at Donaldson Lufkin &amp; Jenrette,
says Oscar nominations will do more to help movies that
haven't had "such broad visibility," like "Awakenings." He
also believes "Goodfellas" could get a boost by being put
back in theaters because at $41 million in ticket sales it
hasn't saturated the potential audience yet.
   Among the most closely watched films in the nominations
race is "Godfather Part III." As the sequel to two movies
that both won best picture, it has a tough act to follow, and
its critical reception has been mixed. Although it had seven
Golden Globe nominations, it came away without any awards.
   For Paramount, a unit of Paramount Communications Inc.,
"Godfather Part III" has been a disappointment so far; it
cost about $55 million to produce and has sold only about
$62.5 million of tickets. The movie is losing momentum fast,
dropping off about 40% last weekend. Paramount executives say
they have higher hopes for overseas markets, which often
account for a larger share of some films' box office. The
movie will be released overseas starting Feb. 22.
   Hopeful of nominations for "Godfather III," Paramount
plans to increase the number of theaters, now at about 602,
to 750 as of Friday. But Mr. Manson questions whether Oscar
nominations will help. "Much stronger than the pull of any
Oscar nominations was the historical following that the
Godfather movies had, and most of that audience has already
seen the movie," he says. "After a strong opening it didn't
seem to have what the film industry calls legs, so it will
have to be more popular internationally for them to make
money."
