<DESCRIPT>  CELEBRITY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  'AFTER being a public person for 25 years, being a public person even as a
pubescent, I have grown used to it. Anybody in public life devises a way to
have some privacy. I really don't think about it very much. I think I am the
same person I have always been. . . . I like to spend the day alone. . . . I
think I am a loner, a very solitary person. This is why I like Paris -- you
are alone but with others. I enjoy eating alone. I am not lonely. I never
was.";   That's from the remarkable Jodie Foster -- child and adult actress
extraordinaire, Oscar-winner, recent Time cover subject, fledgling director.
Foster has been an actress since the age of 4. She's now 28 and shows not the
slightest sign of career ennui -- she is ambitious, attractive, highly
versatile and bankable.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  PRIVACY IS A FAVORITE FOSTER SCENE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Grapevine  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     It would not be hyperbole to say Foster is -- next to Meryl Streep -- the
most seriously regarded female film actor in America. I spoke to Foster last
week. She called from her car phone.;   Foster is everywhere these days,
publicizing her marvelous "Little Man Tate" movie. She both starred in and
directed this tale of a child prodigy caught between his waitress mother
(Foster) and a brilliant child psychologist (Dianne Wiest) who wants to take
him away and "nurture" his genius -- expose him to Mozart and the greats. I
told Foster it was interesting that the screenplay didn't bother much
explaining the character she played -- aside from the fact she was a single
mother with a genius kid.;   Foster: "Well, 28 percent of the population is
made up of kids and single parents. So we are going to have to start figuring
out how to deal with all these people who are in society and yet do not lead
what we call 'conventional' lives.";   Liz: "How did you get that incredible
-- and very untypical -- performance out of Dianne Wiest? She has never been
better.";   Jodie: "She allowed herself to be different from her real self. We
talked a lot about her character, Jane, before we did the film, and I gave her
some research on child prodigies and the adults they grow up to be -- she has
a wide variety of reactions in this movie.";   LIz: "Is there going to be a
sequel to 'Silence of the Lambs'?";   Foster: "Oh, I certainly hope so!";  
Liz: "Do you generally do a lot of research for a movie, or do you just throw
yourself into it unprepared?";   Jodie: "Usually one throws oneself in
unprepared. Like in 'The Accused,' I simply started and that was that. Which
is probably just as well; I might have lost my mind if I had to research
violent rape -- I might have gone crazy."  </TEXT>
