<LEADPARA>  Woody Allen announced Wednesday he will leave financially troubled Orion
Pictures and make his next film for Tri-Star Pictures.;   Allen's relationship
with Orion was one Hollywood's most enduring. It covers his films of the last
10 years, including "Hannah and Her Sisters," "Alice," "Another Woman," "The
Purple Rose of Cairo," "Broadway Danny Rose" and "Zelig."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ORION'S PICTURE DIMS: WOODY ALLEN TO LEAVE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Few Allen films have been financial blockbusters, but the
actor-writer-director is among the most prestigious contemporary filmmakers.
His "Annie Hall," a United Artists release in 1977, won the Oscar for best
picture.;   According to sources familiar with Orion who refused to be named,
Allen was forced to leave Orion when it became obvious the small New
York-based studio lacked funding for his next, still-untitled project.;  
Despite such recent hits as "The Silence of the Lambs" and "Dances With
Wolves," Orion missed a $50 million interest payment last Friday. It has been
negotiating with creditors and has raised the possibility of bankruptcy.;  
"Every dedicated filmmaker I know is rooting for Orion to return to its old
form and rightly so, because as studios go, they don't come any finer," Allen
said in a statement.;   In a statement, Orion said it expects Allen to return
to the studio to complete three more films.;   An Orion spokesman didn't
return a telephone call.;   Debt-strapped Orion still intends to release
Allen's recently completed movie, "Shadows and Fog," next year. It stars Jodie
Foster, Madonna and Allen's companion, Mia Farrow.;   Filming for Allen's new
film at Tri-Star is expected to begin in November, the studio said.  </TEXT>
