<DESCRIPT>  CELEBRITY; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  JODIE FOSTER; (box) Stress can be good for you  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  West  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  WEST CLOSE-UPS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>  "Little Man Tate" marks Foster's directing debut. Directing has been fruitful
for Warren Beatty, Robert Redford and Kevin Costner, who all won Oscars for
their directing but never for their acting. But Foster already has an Oscar,
so why branch out? "I love the stress of directing," she told Premiere. "I
really do. What's great is I can answer all the questions, but I don't have to
perform all the tasks. I'm finding that acting is a thousand times more
debilitating, because you're constantly trying to please someone. I find that
kind of stress factor more difficult than the one of being asked a million
questions and being the head banana." Of course, the roles Foster has chosen
-- the FBI trainee in "The Silence of the Lambs," the rape victim in "The
Accused" -- may account for some of the stress in acting. But she's not about
to give that up: "I always identify with the underdog, not the overlord. So I
either want to play them or play in films that support them and have something
to say about them."; AL PACINO; (box) Never look back; After an absence from
films of almost five years, Pacino made a big comeback in 1989 with "Sea of
Love," and he hasn't stopped working since. His latest film is "Frankie and
Johnny," with Michelle Pfeiffer. "I do sense a change in me and it could be a
turning point," Pacino told Garth Pearce. "I have never really wanted to make
a total commitment to films until now. If you say it's a lesson, then I've
learned it. I think I have finally realized what is possible on film. For
someone like me who was reared only on theater, and still loves it, then the
chance to really examine your character in a movie only comes up rarely. So
when film parts used to come my way I turned them down. There are a couple I
might do now, if only I had the chance, but it does not help anyone to look
back on what might have been." Nor does he look back on what was: "I do not
watch my own films and my opinion is always questionable. Even with 'The
Godfather' I did not watch 'Part I' or 'Part II.' I did the third -- which I
haven't seen -- without looking over my shoulder at what went down in those
days."; TWIGGY LAWSON; (box) Half of the name's the same; The gaunt British
model who epitomized '60s London, the era of Carnaby Street and mods and
rockers, is now 42, starring in an American sitcom, "Princesses," and sporting
a last name. "I can't drop Twiggy," she told Ivor Davis. "It's a nickname and
I'm stuck with it for life. But now I'm calling myself Twiggy Lawson. I just
want to make myself sound more like a human being as opposed to a kind of pet
animal." The Lawson comes from her husband, actor Leigh Lawson. Viewers
looking for the cockney sparrow she once was will be disappointed. "Sure
there's a preconceived image of what I am and what I look like," she says,
"but all actresses you speak to have problems of some sort."; STEVE MARTIN;
(box) A mid-life crisis for comedians?; Martin will be seen this fall in the
remake of "Father of the Bride," in the Spencer Tracy role. Some actors might
shy from the comparison, but Martin may just be testing his limits as an
actor. "When I was in college studying philosophy, I had this chart of when
people do their best work," he told Movieline. "With poets it was generally 20
to 25; philosophers started at 75 to 90. Comedy comes in the mid-30s to
mid-40s. Like Jerry Lewis. (Bob Hope) proves the case, because he was
brilliant and then became a card-reader." Could it be that Martin, who is in
his mid-40s, is seeing what's in the cards?  </TEXT>
