<LEADPARA>  WHO'S the biggest draw on the lecture circuit right now? Not, as you might
expect, either Generals Colin Powell or Norman Schwarzkopf. It's said that
Great Britain's former Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher commands an all-time
high fee of $50,000! (Of course, Powell and Schwarzkopf haven't had much time
recently to sit and chit and chat. When they do, they may put Maggie in the
shade.);    HEARTS THROB: Matt Dillon is not only the talk of Universal, which
is releasing his latest movie, "A Kiss Before Dying," he is the subject of
excited comment throughout filmland circles. The advance buzz is that this is
the one that will finally put Dillon over the top and into the first class,
big money, big star, leading man status enjoyed by the likes of Tom Cruise and
Kevin Costner.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THATCHER APPEARANCE FEE: 50 GRAND  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Grapevine  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     -- Liz Smith;    MORE HORROR: If you're a fan of "Silence of the Lambs" --
with its graphically gruesome details -- you should be pleased to know that
Orion Pictures is already moving to put together a sequel. Word is that story
and script are in discussion for a new chapter in the twisted study of serial
killer Dr. Hannibal Lecter, with the hopes of Anthony Hopkins reprising that
role -- and his relationship with FBI trainee Clarice Starling (Jodie
Foster).;    -- Stacy Jenel Smith; DRAMA CONTINUES: Producer Julia Phillips
reports that movie/music mogul David Geffen "is trying to fire me" from the
film adaptations of Anne Rice's vampire novels.;    Though Geffen has not been
available for comment about the matter, such an action would come as no
surprise, considering the poison darts she aims at him -- and scores of others
in the industry -- in her scathing new Random House "You'll Never Eat Lunch in
This Town Again" autobiography.;    Phillips (a super success as a producer of
such blockbusters as "The Sting," "Taxi Driver" and "Close Encounters of the
Third Kind" before drugs and drink took their toll) secured film rights to the
Rice works seven years ago and made a deal for their adaptations with Warners.
She says Geffen acquired the projects from her last year, but she expected to
stay aboard as producer when any (or all) of them were adapted to screen.
Until now.;    -- Marilyn Beck;    BUY THE BOOK: In Washington these days, the
book that everybody wants to get his hands on is Ronald Kessler's upcoming
expose with the jaw-breaking title, "Escape From the CIA: How the CIA Won and
Lost the Most Important KGB Spy to Ever Defect to The U.S." This comes from
Pocket Books in May. NASTY RESPONSE: The woman whose experience was the basis
for Germany's Oscar-nominated "The Nasty Girl" has not become a heroine to her
townsfolk. Anja Rosmus is being chilled out because she blew the whistle on
all the people back in Passau, Germany, who were die-hard Nazi sympathizers.
And now comes word that Passau will be the locale for an extremist neo-Nazi
convention, celebrating Hitler's birthday. Local bakers are said to be vying
with each other making swastika-shaped breads! As disgusting and unbelievable
as this sounds, it's for real.;    -- Liz Smith; :  </TEXT>
