<CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Baldwin, PHOTO: Basinger deny having trouble on set of
their Disney film.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  CELEBRITY; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  IT'S tension time for the troops on Disney's "The Marrying Man." The film
returns to the cameras today for reshooting of its elaborate wedding sequence
-- in the wake of public airing of the on-set friction between the team of
Alec Baldwin and Kim Basinger and most everyone else in the company, it would
seem.;    The February issue of Premiere Magazine describes principal
production of the film last summer as a nightmare of continuous tantrums and
uncooperative behavior by Basinger and Baldwin -- who late last week issued a
statement calling the allegations "either distorted or outright lies." Baldwin
and Basinger also said, "We chose not to do publicity for 'The Marrying Man'
because the movie Disney made is not the movie we agreed to do."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  'MARRYING MAN' BACK TO THE TRENCHES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Grapevine  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Whether it is or not, "They're going to show up for the (new) shooting,"
says producer David Permut.;    Disney is putting heavy new funding into the
movie -- not only to bring Basinger and Baldwin back to the cameras, but
co-stars Robert Loggia and Elizabeth Shue as well.;    Permut confirms the
shoot has necessitated "building new sets and hiring several hundred extras.
The wedding is really a totally new scene -- the cost is considerable.";   
According to Permut, "Marrying Man" has done well in test screenings. "We're
elated with it -- but we felt we could strengthen it by reshooting some
scenes, primarily the wedding. Frankly, (Disney's) extra investment speaks
very well of their commitment to the film and their confidence about its
potential." Asked about his two stars, Permut replies, "I'll only say this:
'Marrying Man' was the greatest experience of my life. I learned a lot.";   
VERY INTERESTING: The announcement that Warner Bros.'s "Batman II" will start
production this year -- likely in the summer -- with Tim Burton directing, is
gaining much attention. But we'll believe the picture's rolling when we see
it. Burton said just last month that there was no way of telling when a script
for the film would be ready -- and that he couldn't imagine it going into
production this year or next.;    MIXED MEDIA: With his "Silence of the Lambs"
thriller starring Jodie Foster due to open for Orion next month, filmmaker
Jonathan Demme has made a deal to direct three more features for the firm. The
first will likely be "Fatal Voyage," based on Dan Kurzman's best seller about
World War II's ill-fated U.S.S. Indianapolis, which, with the Stacy Keach
"Mission of the Shark" telepic upcoming for CBS, means two projects about the
ship are on the boards.;    Sally Field's "Conundrum," which was slated for
shooting last year, is still a long way from being ready for screen. Field
says the psychological thriller in which she's supposed to play a police
investigator "is still in development (at Pathe). We have no idea when it will
go into production." She's been attached to the project for more than two
years.;    Ted Turner has signed screenwriter Edward Anhalt to write his
"Alexander the Great" movie script.;    CASTING CORNER: Martin Mull does a
guest turn on Fox's "Get a Life" as talk-show host Sandy Connors. In the
"Chris Wins a Celebrity" segment shooting this week, Chris Peterson (Chris
Elliott) enters a contest 3,000 times to win a weekend with Connors, his
favorite talk-show host. A weekend turns into a month when Mull's character
decides to quit his TV show to live a carefree life with the Petersons.;   
WHEN IN JAPAN: Debbie Shapiro, the Tony Award-winning star of "Jerome Robbins'
Broadway" is taking a crash course in Japanese -- to prepare for the show's
run in Japan that commences in March. The "Broadway" songs will be performed
in English, but the cast will perform the speaking parts in Japanese.  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  From Marilyn Beck and Stacy Jenel Smith in Hollywood  </BYLINE>
