<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Peter and Captain Hook have at it in the Disney classic. Now
Spielberg's readying his version.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  MOVIE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  ABOUT six years ago, as the rights to the James M. Barrie story were about to
revert to public domain, Steven Spielberg began talking about a live-action
version of "Peter Pan," co-starring Michael Jackson as Peter and perhaps
veteran meanie Christopher Lee as Captain Hook.;    It sounded like a union
made in Neverland -- the classic fairy tale about the boy who refused to grow
up by the filmmaker who refused to grow up.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  A YOUNG-AT-HEART DIRECTOR PREPARES A RETURN
TO THE LOST BOYS OF NEVERLAND
SPIELBERG'S 'PETER PAN' COMPLEX  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Film  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     For a number of reasons -- the unavailability of Jackson and the success of
Spielberg's Indiana Jones series among them -- Spielberg never got around to
his ultimate celluloid fantasy.;    It was probably for the best. At the time,
the director of "E.T." and "Jaws" was being criticized for not tackling
grown-up problems on screen. Spielberg's counterpunch: the achingly relevant
"The Color Purple" and "Empire of the Sun." Spielberg was clearly out of his
league. Even his detractors conceded that the juvenile Spielberg was
preferable to the socially conscious Spielberg who clunked about in David
Lean's vastly over-sized boots.;    Spielberg, now obviously more at peace
with himself, has returned to the Peter Pan project. But it won't be the story
we all remember from the Disney cartoon feature and the Mary Martin musical.; 
  Spielberg's spin, titled simply "Hook" and taken from a story by Jim V. Hart
and Nick ("The Boy Who Could Fly") Castle, sounds like the perfect balm for
age-obsessed baby boomers.;    It will feature Robin Williams as an adult Pan,
Dustin Hoffman as an Actors Studio version of Captain Hook (Capt. Mumbles?),
Bob Hoskins as first-mate Smee and Maggie Smith as the ninetysomething "Gran"
Wendy, who, unlike Peter, has had to deal with the ravages of real time.
(Peter ages during his short sojourn from Neverland.);    And who has
Spielberg nabbed for that mischievous faerie Tinkerbell? Would you believe
Julia Roberts? Tink has always been accused of being something of a vixen and
sex symbol. This may be even more the case with the sensuous Roberts in the
role. At the very least, we can expect a strong undercurrent of sexual
tension. Wendy's now too old for Peter, and Tinkerbell, who has always had a
thing for Peter, is much too small.;    Look for this Peter to tarry longer
than usual with the voluptuous inhabitants of Mermaids Lagoon.;    It's either
that, or the screenwriters will have to introduce a youth potion for Wendy and
a growth vitamin for Tink.;    Apart from the obvious thematic problems posed
by an 80-years-later return to Neverland, there also is that lingering
industry admonition -- Thou Shalt Not Go Home Again (particularly when it
comes to raiding family perennials).;    Think back. When was the last time
you saw a satisfying sequel or modernization of a family classic?;    "The
Wiz," a Motown spin on "The Wizard of Oz," offered a much-too-old Diana Ross
scampering through an inner-city version of Oz. Disney's "Return to Oz"
boomeranged by traumatizing its target audience with a heavily Freudian
continuation of Dorothy's travels. And don't forget what one enterprising
playwright did to Huck Finn and Tom Sawyer. He had them return 60 years later
as a drunkard and a child-molester, played by Burt Lancaster and Kirk Douglas
in a work-in-progress called "The Boys of Autumn" that mercifully never made
it to Broadway.;    So, you see, Spielberg and company have their work cut out
for them. This tinkering (no pun intended) with childhood favorites can be as
hazardous to your health as a swim around Pirates Cove with that tick-tocking
crocodile in hot pursuit.;    "Hook" begins production at Columbia Studios on
Feb. 19. It will be designed by Norman Garwood ("Brazil"), photographed by
Dean Cundey ("Who Framed Roger Rabbit") and scored by Spielberg's favorite
composer, five-time Oscar winner John Williams ("Jaws," "Raiders of the Lost
Ark"). It's scheduled to open around Christmastime.; (hbox);    'LAMBS' TO THE
SLAUGHTER -- Menlo Park audiences were treated to a most unusual double bill
Saturday night -- Woody Allen's "Alice" and a special sneak preview of
Jonathan Demme's "The Silence of the Lambs" (opening Feb. 14). The first deals
in sophisticated screwball comedy; the second, based on the Thomas Harris
best-seller about a pair of psychos and a rookie FBI agent, pushes cold-sweat
suspense. So did the capacity "Alice" crowd stick around for the year's most
eagerly awaited thriller, co-starring Jodie Foster and Anthony Hopkins? Are
you kidding? Allen may draw in the tony university town, but gruesome
cut-'em-ups don't. The theater practically cleared out, leaving plenty of
seats for the Demme contingent, obviously from out of town.  </TEXT>
