<LEADPARA>  Director Jonathan Demme told reporters that when he set out to film "The
Silence of the Lambs," the fact that cannibalism plays a key theme in the
Thomas Harris crime thriller posed certain casting problems.;    Demme
imagined Michelle Pfeiffer in the role of the tale's heroine, "but Michelle
very swiftly came to feel troubled by the, um, darkness of the material."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  A DELICIOUS PART FOR ANTHONY HOPKINS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  People.
Compiled from Mercury News wire services.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Into the void stepped Jodie Foster, who, as it turned out, is an avid fan
of Harris' novels.;    Casting the role of the killer Hannibal the Cannibal
proved far less difficult.;    "I hate to make the unavoidable pun," says
Demme, obviously not hating it at all, "but it's a delicious part. It's just
scrumptious.";    Of the many actors who vied for the role, Anthony Hopkins,
the director says, was his first and only choice.  </TEXT>
