</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Orion Pictures Corp., still seeking cash to
ease a liquidity crunch, reported the biggest box office
weekend in its history, grabbing about 25% of the market.
   Orion said its four films -- "Dances With Wolves,"
"Silence of the Lambs," "Mermaids" and "Alice" -- grossed an
estimated $20.9 million. Although final figures aren't in
until today, entertainment data concern Baseline Inc. said
Orion may have inched past Fox Film, a unit of News Corp.,
which has been the industry box office leader for several
weekends.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Most of Orion's revenue came from "Dances With Wolves,"
which was nominated for twelve Academy Awards including Best
Picture last week; it grossed about $6.2 million last weekend
for an estimated total of about $111.7 million. Orion appears
to have another big hit with "Silence of the Lambs," which
has grossed an impressive $13.7 million since its opening
last Thursday.
   But despite its current success, the company still needs
operating funds to carry it through the year. Orion is
attempting to raise $75 million to $100 million by selling
rights to five films that are in production or finished.
   Longer-term, Orion is also seeking to raise funds from a
new equity investor. Billionaire John Kluge, who controls 70%
of Orion, recently provided $23 million in cash in return for
a big cut of profits from "Mermaids," and possibly "Silence
of the Lambs."
</TEXT>
