<DESCRIPT>  CELEBRITY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  BROADWAY lights up this fall, thanks to producers Jimmy Nederlander and Stan
Seiden. These are the men who will present the long-awaited "Sugar Babies II."
This all new state-of-the-art burlesque will star Jerry Lewis, Chita Rivera
and Rip Taylor. Ralph Allen, who co-conceived the original, will direct. Scott
Salmon will choreograph.;    The show is to tour L.A. and San Francisco before
finally settling in at the Minskoff in New York. You may recall that "Sugar
Babies" starred Mickey Rooney and Ann Miller. Opening in October 1979, it
played 1,036 performances at the Mark Hellinger, successfully toured the U.S.
and England and totally revitalized the careers of Rooney and Miller. (Lest we
forget, the last time Lewis was Broadway bound, in "Hellzapoppin," all that
came out of it was a collector's-item poster of a show that didn't happen.)  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  'SUGAR BABIES II' BROADWAY-BOUND  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Grapevine  </MEMO>
<TEXT>      WEDDING SHEDDING: Now that 600 people who were planning to be on the Fox
lot Friday for the wedding of Julia Roberts and Kiefer Sutherland have nothing
whatsoever to do, let's think on this interesting cancellation.;    Believe it
or not, there are many who have sighed great big sighs of relief that the
marriage has been "postponed by mutual consent." Roberts is under incredible
pressure at the moment -- both from her burgeoning fame and from her enormous
workload. (She now commands $7 million per film, and she's expected to
deliver.) This has to mean that Sutherland is also under incredible pressure.
Roberts needs to take that planned year's hiatus from work before she makes a
major marital decision; after all, she is only 23 years old.;    HARD-WORKING
HANNIBAL: Anthony Hopkins' hypnotic and terrifying performance in the smash
hit "The Silence of the Lambs" is a shoo-in for Oscar consideration next year.
But Hopkins has many projects on his plate before he can even think about that
much-hoped-for sequel to "Lambs" and a reprise of the sinister Hannibal
Lecter.;    The actor is in England now, filming "Howard's End" with Vanessa
Redgrave. (This is the Merchant-Ivory production from yet another novel by
E.M. Forster. Their movie based on the same author's "A Room With a View" was
a great success.) And Hopkins is currently in negotiation to star as the
vampire-hunting scholar, Prof. Van Helsing, in Francis Ford Coppola's new
version of "Dracula," for which Winona Ryder has already been signed.; From
Marilyn Beck and Stacy Jenel Smith in Hollywood;    REVOLVING DOOR: Looks like
Julia Duffy, who's bowed out of ABC's "Baby Talk," will be joining the
"Designing Women" cast. Meanwhile, practically everything about "Baby Talk" is
being changed -- with the exception of the twin infants who play the baby, and
Tony Danza, who narrates their voices. Auditions are taking place week for a
replacement Duffy. And Saul Turtletaub, one of the new executive producers,
says new writers have been hired and a fresh batch of supporting players will
be cast. "We'll be moving the action from the loft to an apartment building
and adding neighbors, a building supervisor, and possibly a boss."  </TEXT>
<BYLINE>  From Liz Smith in New York  </BYLINE>
